# Apex

## Bulkification

Assume 200+ records per transaction. No SOQL, SOSL, or DML inside loops — collect
into maps/sets and operate on collections. For large volumes use Batch or Queueable,
not synchronous loops.

## Governor limits

Query only the fields you use. Keep `WHERE` clauses selective on indexed fields for
large objects. Avoid nested loops over large lists.

## Triggers

One trigger per object. No logic in the trigger body — delegate to a handler class.
Guard against recursion.

## Security

Enforce CRUD/FLS before every read and write (`WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED`,
`Security.stripInaccessible`, or explicit `isAccessible`/`isUpdateable` checks).
Declare `with sharing` unless there's a documented reason not to. Use bind
variables, never string-concatenated SOQL.

## Errors

Catch specific exceptions and throw a meaningful custom exception; don't swallow
them. Log through the project logging framework, never `System.debug` of sensitive
fields.
